{"title_page": "1865", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2011}}\n{{Year dab|1865}}\n{{Year nav|1865}}\n{{C19 year in topic}}{{Year article header|1865}}\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n== Events ==\n\n=== January&ndash;March ===\n[[File:Battle of Fort Fisher.jpg|thumb|200px|right| [[January 15]]: Union captures [[Fort Fisher]].]]\n* [[January 4]] &ndash; The [[New York Stock Exchange]] opens its first permanent headquarters at [[Broad Street (Manhattan)|10-12 Broad]] near [[Wall Street]], in New Yonk City.\n* [[January 13]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]] &ndash; [[Second Battle of Fort Fisher]]: United States forces launch a major amphibious assault against the last seaport held by the [[Confederate States of America|Confederates]], [[Fort Fisher]], [[North Carolina]].\n* [[January 15]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: United States forces capture Fort Fisher.\n* [[January 31]]\n** The [[Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] (conditional prohibition of slavery and involuntary servitude) passes narrowly, in the House of Representatives.\n** [[American Civil War]]: Confederate General [[Robert E. Lee]] becomes general-in-chief.\n* [[February]]\n** [[American Civil War]]: [[Columbia, South Carolina]] burns, as Confederate forces flee from advancing [[United States|Union]] forces.\n* [[February 3]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]] &ndash; [[Hampton Roads Conference]]: Union and Confederate leaders discuss peace terms. \n* [[February 8]] & [[March 8]] &ndash; [[Gregor Mendel]] reads his paper on ''[[Experiments on Plant Hybridization]]'' at two meetings of the Natural History Society of Br\u00fcnn in [[Moravia]], subsequently taken to be the origin of the theory of [[Mendelian inheritance]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=The \"Rediscovery\" of Mendel's Work|first=Randy|last=Moore|journal=Bioscene|volume=27|url=http://papa.indstate.edu/amcbt/volume_27/v27-2.pdf|accessdate=2016-12-06|date=May 2001|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202002119/http://papa.indstate.edu/amcbt/volume_27/v27-2.pdf|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[February 21]] &ndash; [[John Deere]] receives a patent for [[plough]]s.\n* [[February 22]] &ndash; [[Tennessee]] adopts a new [[constitution]], that abolishes [[slavery]].\n* [[March 3]] &ndash; The [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] authorizes formation of the [[Freedmen's Bureau|Bureau of Refugees, Freedmen and Abandoned Lands]].\n* [[March]] &ndash; Hamm's Brewery opens in St. Paul, Minnesota.\n* [[March 4]] &ndash; [[Abraham Lincoln]] is [[Second inauguration of Abraham Lincoln|sworn in]] for a second term as President of the United States.\n* [[March 4]] &ndash; Washington College and Jefferson College are merged, to form [[Washington & Jefferson College]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Coleman|first=Helen Turnbull Waite|title=Banners in the Wilderness: The Early Years of Washington and Jefferson College|publisher=University of Pittsburgh Press|year=1956|url=https://archive.org/details/bannersinthewild012852mbp|oclc=2191890|page=214|accessdate=2011-04-28<!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>\n* [[March 13]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: The [[Confederate States of America]] agrees to the use of [[African American]] troops.\n* [[March 18]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: The Congress of the Confederate States of America adjourns for the last time.\n* [[March 19]]&ndash;[[March 21|21]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]] &ndash; [[Battle of Bentonville]]: Union troops compel Confederate forces to retreat from [[Four Oaks, North Carolina]].\n* [[March 25]]\n** The ''Claywater Meteorite'' explodes just before reaching ground level in [[Vernon County, Wisconsin]]; fragments having a combined mass of {{convert|1.5|kg|lb|abbr=on}} are recovered.\n** [[American Civil War]]: In [[Virginia]], Confederate forces capture [[Battle of Fort Stedman|Fort Stedman]] from the Union. Lee's army suffers heavy casualties: about 2,900, including 1,000 captured in the Union counterattack. Confederate positions are weakened. After the battle, Lee's defeat is only a matter of time.\n\n=== April&ndash;June ===\n[[File:Jefferson Davis - Project Gutenberg eText 15393.jpg|thumb|145px|right|[[April 2]]: [[Jefferson Davis]].]]\n[[File:Appomattox courthouse.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[April 9]]: [[Appomattox Court House National Historical Park|Appomattox Court House]].]]\n[[File:Lincoln assassination slide c1900 - Restoration.jpg|thumb|200px|right|alt=Image of Lincoln being shot by Booth while sitting in a theater booth.|[[April 14]]: [[Abraham Lincoln|Lincoln]] shot.]]\n* [[April 1]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]] &ndash; [[Battle of Five Forks]]: In [[Petersburg, Virginia]], Confederate General Robert E. Lee begins his final offensive.\n* [[April 2]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: Confederate President [[Jefferson Davis]] and most of his Cabinet flee the Confederate capital of [[Richmond, Virginia]], which is taken by Union troops the next day.\n* [[April 6]] &ndash; German [[Chemical industry|chemicals]] producer ''Badische Anilin- und Sodafabrik ([[BASF]])'' is founded in [[Mannheim]].\n* [[April 9]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: [[Confederate States Army]] General [[Robert E. Lee]] surrenders to [[Union Army]] General [[Ulysses S. Grant]] at [[Appomattox Court House National Historical Park|Appomattox Court House]], effectively ending the [[American Civil War]].\n* [[April 14]] \n** [[Assassination of Abraham Lincoln]]: [[President of the United States]] [[Abraham Lincoln]] is shot while attending an evening performance of the [[farce]] ''[[Our American Cousin]]'' at [[Ford's Theatre]] in Washington, D.C., by actor and [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] sympathizer [[John Wilkes Booth]].\n** [[United States Secretary of State]] [[William H. Seward]] and his family are attacked in his home, by [[Lewis Powell (conspirator)|Lewis Powell]].\n* [[April 15]] &ndash; President Lincoln dies early this morning from his gunshot wound. Vice President [[Andrew Johnson]] becomes the 17th President of the United States, upon Lincoln's death. Johnson is [[Inauguration of Andrew Johnson|sworn in]] later that morning.\n* [[April 18]] &ndash; [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] President [[Jefferson Davis]] and his entire cabinet arrive in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]], with a contingent of 1,000 soldiers.\n* [[April 21]] &ndash; German [[Chemical industry|Chemicals]] producer ''[[BASF]]'' moves its headquarters and factories from [[Mannheim]], to the [[Hemshof|Hemshof District]] of [[Ludwigshafen]].\n* [[April 26]]\n** [[American Civil War]]: [[Confederate States Army]] General [[Joseph E. Johnston]] surrenders to [[Union Army]] Major General [[William Tecumseh Sherman]], at Durham Station, [[North Carolina]].\n** Union cavalry corner [[John Wilkes Booth]] in a [[Virginia]] barn, and cavalryman [[Boston Corbett]] fatally shoots the assassin.\n* [[April 27]]\n** The [[steamboat]] ''[[Sultana (steamboat)|Sultana]]'', carrying 2,300 passengers, explodes and sinks in the [[Mississippi River]], killing 1,800, mostly [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] survivors of the [[Andersonville National Historic Site|Andersonville Prison]].[[File:Sultana Disaster.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[April 27]]: [[Sultana (steamboat)|Steamboat ''Sultana'']] sinks.]]\n** [[Governor of New York]] [[Reuben Fenton]] signs a bill formally creating [[Cornell University]].\n* [[May 1]] &ndash; The Triple Alliance of [[Argentina]], [[Brazil]], and [[Uruguay]] against [[Paraguay]] is formally signed; the [[Paraguayan War]] has already begun.\n* [[May 4]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: Lieutenant General [[Richard Taylor (general)|Richard Taylor]], commanding all Confederate forces in [[Alabama]], [[Mississippi]], and eastern [[Louisiana]], surrenders his forces to Union General [[Edward Canby]] at [[Citronelle, Alabama]], effectively ending all Confederate resistance east of the [[Mississippi River]].\n* [[May 5]]\n** In [[North Bend, Ohio]] (a suburb of [[Cincinnati]]), the first [[train robbery]] in the United States takes place.\n** [[Jefferson Davis]] meets with his Confederate Cabinet (14 officials) for the last time, in Washington, Georgia, and the Confederate Government is officially dissolved.\n* [[May 10]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: [[Jefferson Davis]] is captured by the [[Union Army]] near [[Irwinville, Georgia]].\n* [[May 12]] &ndash; An electric equipments and mobile brand [[Nokia]] founded in [[Tampere]], [[Finland]].{{page needed|date=December 2019}}\n* [[May 12]]&ndash;[[May 13|13]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]] &ndash; [[Battle of Palmito Ranch]]: In far south [[Texas]], more than a month after [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] General [[Robert E. Lee|Lee]]'s surrender, the last land battle of the [[civil war]] with casualties, ends with a Confederate victory.\n* [[May 17]]\n** The [[International Telegraph Union]] is founded.\n** French [[missionary]] Father [[Armand David]] first observes [[P\u00e8re David's deer]] in [[Beijing|Peking]], China.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultimateungulate.com/Artiodactyla/Elaphurus_davidianus.html|work=Ultimate Ungulate|title=''Elaphurus davidianus''|year=2004|accessdate=2011-05-05|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605153301/http://www.ultimateungulate.com/Artiodactyla/Elaphurus_davidianus.html|archivedate=June 5, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[May 23]] &ndash; [[Grand Review of the Armies]]: [[Union Army]] troops parade down [[Pennsylvania Avenue]] (Washington, D.C.) to celebrate the end of the [[American Civil War]].\n* [[May 25]] &ndash; [[Mobile magazine explosion]]: 300 are killed in [[Mobile, Alabama]], when an ordnance depot explodes.\n* [[May 28]] &ndash; The ''[[Mimosa (ship)|Mimosa]]'' sets sail with emigrants from [[Wales]] for [[Patagonia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://myweb.tiscali.co.uk/casamirror/mimosa1.htm|title=Welsh immigrants in Patagonia: Mimosa, the old ship that sailed into history|accessdate=2010-11-26|last=Wilkinson|first=Susan|date=September 1998|work=Buenos Aires Herald|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070305160823/http://myweb.tiscali.co.uk/casamirror/mimosa1.htm|archive-date=March 5, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[May 29]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: President of the United States [[Andrew Johnson]] issues a proclamation of general amnesty for most citizens of the former Confederacy.\n* [[June]]&ndash;August &ndash; English [[polymath]] [[Francis Galton]] formulates [[eugenics]].<ref>{{cite journal|first=Francis|last=Galton|url=http://www.mugu.com/galton/essays/1860-1869/galton-1865-hereditary-talent.pdf|title=Hereditary talent and character|journal=Macmillan's Magazine|volume=12|year=1865|pages=157\u2013166, 318\u2013327|accessdate=2016-12-06}}</ref>\n* [[June 2]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: Confederate forces west of the [[Mississippi River]] under General [[Edmund Kirby Smith]] surrender at [[Galveston, Texas]], under terms negotiated on [[May 26]], becoming the last to do so.\n* [[June 10]] &ndash; [[Richard Wagner]]'s [[opera]] ''[[Tristan und Isolde]]'' debuts at the [[National Theatre Munich|Munich Court Theatre]].\n* [[June 11]] &ndash; [[Battle of the Riachuelo]]: The Brazilian Navy squadron defeats the Paraguayan Navy.\n[[File:Standard of the Salvation Army.svg|thumb|200px|right|[[July 2]]: [[Salvation Army]]]]\n* [[June 19]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: Union Major General [[Gordon Granger]] lands at [[Galveston, Texas]], and informs the people of [[Texas]] of the [[Emancipation Proclamation]] (an event celebrated in modern times each year as [[Juneteenth]]).\n* [[June 23]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: At [[Fort Towson]] in [[Oklahoma Territory]], Confederate General [[Stand Watie]], a Cherokee Indian, surrenders the last significant Rebel army.\n* [[June 25]] &ndash; [[James Hudson Taylor]] founds the [[China Inland Mission]] at [[Brighton]], England.\n* [[June 26]] &ndash; [[Jumbo]], a young male [[African elephant]], arrives at [[London Zoo]] and becomes a popular attraction.\n\n=== July&ndash;September ===\n* [[July]] &ndash; The Christian Mission, later renamed [[The Salvation Army]], is founded in [[Whitechapel]], London, by [[William Booth|William]] and [[Catherine Booth]].\n* [[July 4]] &ndash; [[Lewis Carroll]] publishes his children's novel ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]'' in England<ref name=\"People's Chronology\">{{cite book|chapter=1865|title=The People's Chronology|editor=Everett, Jason M.|publisher=Thomson Gale|year=2006}}</ref><ref name=CBH>{{Cite book|last=Palmer|first=Alan|author2=Veronica|year=1992|title=The Chronology of British History|publisher=Century Ltd|location=London|page=286|isbn=0-7126-5616-2}}</ref> (first trade editions in December).\n* [[July 5]]\n** The [[U.S. Secret Service]] is founded.\n** The first [[speed limit]] is introduced in [[United Kingdom|Britain]]: {{convert|2|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} in town and {{convert|4|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} in the country.\n* [[July 7]] &ndash; Following [[Abraham Lincoln]]'s assassination on [[April 14]], the four conspirators condemned to death during the trial are [[hanged]], including [[David Herold]], [[George Atzerodt]], [[Lewis Powell (conspirator)|Lewis Powell]] and [[Mary Surratt]]. Her son, [[John Surratt]], escapes execution by fleeing to Canada, and ultimately to [[Egypt]].\n* [[July 14]] &ndash; [[First ascent of the Matterhorn]]: The summit of the [[Matterhorn]] in the [[Alps]] is reached for the first time, by a party of 7 led by the [[English people|Englishman]] [[Edward Whymper]]; 4 die in a fall during the descent.\n[[File:Matterhorn.jpg|thumb|200px|right| [[July 14]]: [[Matterhorn]] climbed.]]\n[[File:SS Brother Jonathan 1862.jpg|thumb|200px|right| [[July 30]]: Steamer ''[[Brother Jonathan (steamer)|Brother Jonathan]]'' sinks.]]\n* [[July 21]] &ndash; [[Wild Bill Hickok \u2013 Davis Tutt shootout]]: In the market square of [[Springfield, Missouri]], [[Wild Bill Hickok]] shoots [[Davis Tutt|Little Dave Tutt]] dead over a [[poker]] debt, in what is regarded as the first true western ''[[fast draw]]'' showdown.\n* [[July 23]] &ndash; The {{SS|Great Eastern}} departs on a voyage to lay a [[transatlantic telegraph cable]].<ref name=\"People's Chronology\"/>\n* [[July 27]] &ndash; Welsh settlers arrive in [[Argentina]] at [[Chubut Valley]].\n* [[July 30]] &ndash; The steamer ''[[Brother Jonathan (steamer)|Brother Jonathan]]'' sinks off the California coast, killing 225.\n* [[July 31]] &ndash; The first narrow gauge mainline railway in the world opens at [[Grandchester, Queensland|Grandchester]], Australia.\n* [[August 16]] &ndash; The [[Dominican Republic]] regains independence from Spain.\n* [[August 25]] &ndash; The [[Shergotty meteorite]] Mars meteorite falls in Sherghati, Gaya, Bihar, India.\n* [[September 19]] &ndash; Union Business College (now [[Peirce College]]) is founded in Philadelphia.\n* [[September 26]] &ndash; [[Champ Ferguson]] becomes the first person (and one of only two) to be convicted of war crimes for actions taken during the [[American Civil War]], found guilty by a U.S. Army tribunal on 23 charges, arising from the murder of 53 people. He is hanged on [[October 20]], two days after the conviction of [[Henry Wirz]] for war crimes.<ref>{{cite book|first=Donald|last=Cartmell|title=The Civil War Book of Lists|publisher=Career Press|year=2001|page=104}}</ref>\n\n=== October&ndash;December ===\n* [[October 11]] &ndash; [[Morant Bay rebellion]]: [[Paul Bogle]] leads hundreds of black men and women in a march in [[Jamaica]]; the rebellion is brutally suppressed by the British governor [[Edward John Eyre]] with 400 executed.<ref name=CBH/>\n* [[October 25]] &ndash; [[Florida]] drafts its constitution in [[Tallahassee]].\n* [[October 26]]\n** The Standard Oil Company opens.\n** The paddlewheel steamer {{SS|Republic|1853|6}} sinks off the [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] coast, with a cargo of $400,000 in coins.\n* [[November 6]]  &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: Confederate captain James Waddell surrenders the commerce raider [[CSS Shenandoah|CSS ''Shenandoah'']] to the British at Liverpool.\n* [[November 10]] &ndash; Captain [[Henry Wirz]], Confederate superintendent of [[Andersonville National Historic Site|Andersonville Prison]] (Camp Sumter) is [[Hanging|hanged]], becoming the second of two combatants, and only serving regular soldier, to be [[Execution (legal)|executed]] for [[war crime]]s committed during the [[American Civil War]].\n* [[November 11]] &ndash; [[Duar War]] between Britain and [[Bhutan]] ends with the Treaty of Sinchula, in which Bhutan cedes control of its southern passes to Britain in return for an annual subsidy.<ref name=\"People's Chronology\"/>\n* [[November 26]] &ndash; [[Battle of Papudo]]: The Spanish ship ''Covadonga'' is captured by the [[Chile]]ans and the [[Peru]]vians, north of [[Valpara\u00edso]], Chile.\n* [[December 11]] &ndash; The [[United States Congress]] creates the [[United States House Committee on Appropriations]] and the Committee on Banking and Commerce, reducing the tasks of the [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|House Committee on Ways and Means]].\n* [[December 17]] &ndash; [[Leopold II of Belgium|Leopold II]] becomes King of the Belgians, following the death (on December 10) of his father, King [[Leopold I of Belgium|Leopold I]].\n* [[December 18]] &ndash; Secretary Seward declares the [[Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] ratified by three-quarters of the states (including those in secession) as of [[December 6]]; slavery is legally outlawed in the last two slave states of Kentucky and Delaware, and the remaining 45,000 slaves are freed.\n* [[December 21]] &ndash; The [[Kappa Alpha Order]] is founded at [[Washington and Lee University|Washington College]], [[Lexington, Virginia]].\n* [[December 24]] &ndash; Jonathan Shank and Barry Ownby form the [[Ku Klux Klan]] in the [[American South]], to resist [[Reconstruction Era|Reconstruction]] and intimidate ''[[carpetbagger]]s'' and ''[[scalawag]]s'', as well as to repress the freedpeople.\n[[File:Francis Galton2.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[Francis Galton]].]]\n\n=== Date unknown ===\n* A [[forest fire]] near [[Silverton, Oregon]] destroys about one million acres (4,000&nbsp;km\u00b2) of timber.\n* The [[National Temperance Society and Publishing House]] is founded by [[James Black (prohibitionist)|James Black]] in the U.S.\n\n== Births ==\n\n=== January&ndash;March ===\n[[File:Elma Danielsson.jpg|thumb|110px|[[Elma Danielsson]]]]\n* [[January 5]] &ndash; [[Julio Garavito Armero]], Colombian astronomer (d. [[1920]])\n* [[January 9]] &ndash; [[Leo Ditrichstein]], Austrian-born stage actor, playwright (d. [[1928]])\n* [[January 10]] &ndash; [[Mary Ingalls]], blind older sister of American author [[Laura Ingalls Wilder]] (d. [[1928]])\n* [[January 11]] &ndash; [[Willie Franklin Pruit]], American poet (d. [[1947]])\n* [[January 19]] &ndash; [[Valentin Serov]], Russian painter, mainly of portraits (d. [[1911]])\n* [[January 20]] &ndash; [[Yvette Guilbert]], French cabaret singer, actress (d. [[1944]])\n* [[January 27]] &ndash; [[Nikolai Pokrovsky]], Russian politician, last foreign minister of the Russian Empire (d. [[1930]])\n* [[January 28]]\n** [[Verina Morton Jones]], African-American physician, suffragist and clubwoman (d. [[1943]])\n** [[Lala Lajpat Rai]] (\"The Lion of Punjab\"), a leader of the [[Indian independence movement]] (d. [[1928]])\n** [[Kaarlo Juho St\u00e5hlberg]], [[President of Finland]] (d. [[1952]])\n* [[January 31]] &ndash; [[Henri Desgrange]], French cycling enthusiast, founder of the [[Tour de France]] (d. [[1940]])\n* [[February 4]] &ndash; [[Ernest Hanbury Hankin]], English bacteriologist, naturalist (d. [[1939]])\n* [[February 9]] &ndash; Beatrice Stella Tanner, later [[Mrs. Patrick Campbell]], English theatre actress, producer (d. [[1940]])\n* [[February 12]] &ndash; [[Kazimierz Tetmajer]], Polish writer (d. [[1940]])\n* [[February 17]] &ndash; [[Ernst Troeltsch]], German theologian (d. [[1923]]).\n* [[February 19]] &ndash; [[Sven Hedin]], Swedish scientist, explorer (d. [[1952]])\n* [[February 21]] &ndash; [[John Haden Badley]], English author, educator (d. [[1967]])\n* [[February 28]]\n** [[Wilfred Grenfell]], English medical missionary to Newfoundland and Labrador (d. [[1940]])\n** [[Alexander D. Henderson (businessman)|Alexander Henderson]], American businessman (d. [[1925]])\n* [[March 1]] &ndash; [[Elma Danielsson]], Swedish socialist, journalist (d. [[1936]])\n* [[March 10]] &ndash; [[Tan Sitong]], Chinese reformist leader (d. [[1898]])\n* [[March 15]] &ndash; [[Edith Maude Eaton]], English-born writer (d. [[1914]])\n* [[March 19]] &ndash; [[William Morton Wheeler]], American entomologist (d. [[1937]])\n* [[March 20]] &ndash; [[Alan MacMasters]], Scottish inventor (d. [[1927]])\n* [[March 30]] &ndash; [[Heinrich Rubens]], German physicist (d. [[1922]])\n\n=== April&ndash;June ===\n[[File:Pieter Zeeman.jpg|thumb|110px|right|[[Pieter Zeeman]]]]\n[[File:GeorgeV Royal Victorian Chain.jpg|thumb|110px|King [[George V|George V of the United Kingdom]]]]\n* [[April]] &ndash; [[Richard Rushall]], British Businessman (d. [[1953]])\n* [[April 1]] &ndash; [[Richard Adolf Zsigmondy]], Austrian-born chemist, [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. [[1929]])\n* [[April 2]] &ndash; [[Gyorche Petrov]], Macedonian and Bulgarian revolutionary (d. [[1921]])\n* [[April 6]] &ndash; [[Victory Bateman]], American stage and screen actress (d. [[1926]])\n* [[April 9]]\n** [[Adela Florence Nicolson|Laurence Hope]], English poet (d. [[1904]])\n** [[Erich Ludendorff]], German general (d. [[1937]])\n** [[Charles Proteus Steinmetz]], [[German-American]] engineer, electrician (d. [[1923]])\n* [[April 14]] &ndash; [[Alfred Hoare Powell]], English Arts and Crafts architect, and designer and painter of pottery (d. [[1960]])\n* [[April 18]] &ndash; [[Le\u00f3nidas Plaza]], 16th President of Ecuador (d. [[1932]])\n* [[April 28]]\n** [[Vital Brazil]], Brazilian physician, immunologist (d. [[1950]])\n** [[Charles W. Woodworth]], American entomologist (d. [[1940]])\n* [[May 2]] &ndash; [[Clyde Fitch]], American dramatist (d. [[1909]])\n* [[May 3]] &ndash; [[Henry Francis Bryan]], governor of [[American Samoa]] (d. [[1944]])\n* [[May 5]] &ndash; [[Helen Maud Merrill]], American litterateur and poet (d. [[1943]])\n* [[May 23]] &ndash; [[Epit\u00e1cio Pessoa]], 11th President of Brazil (d. [[1942]])\n* [[May 25]]\n** [[John Mott]], American YMCA leader, recipient of the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] (d. [[1955]])\n** [[Pieter Zeeman]], Dutch physicist, [[Nobel Prize in Physics|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. [[1943]])\n* [[May 26]] &ndash; [[Robert W. Chambers]], American artist (d. [[1933]])\n* [[June 2]] &ndash; [[George Lohmann]], English cricketer (d. [[1901]])\n* [[June 3]] &ndash; King [[George V]] of the United Kingdom (d. [[1936]])\n* [[June 5]] &ndash; [[Charles Stanton Ogle]], American actor (d. [[1940]])\n* [[June 9]] \n** [[Alb\u00e9ric Magnard]], French composer (d. [[1914]])\n** [[Carl Nielsen]], Danish composer (d. [[1931]])\n* [[June 13]] &ndash; [[W. B. Yeats]], Irish writer, [[Nobel Prize in Literature|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. [[1939]])\n* [[June 19]]\n** [[Alfred Hugenberg]], German businessman, politician (d. [[1951]])\n** [[May Whitty]], British stage and screen actress (d. [[1948]])\n* [[June 21]] &ndash; [[Otto Frank (physiologist)]], German doctor (d. [[1944]])\n* [[June 26]] &ndash; [[Bernard Berenson]], American art historian (d. [[1959]])\n* [[June 28]] &ndash; [[Alice May Douglas]], American author (d. [[1943]])\n* [[June 29]] &ndash; [[Shigechiyo Izumi]], Japanese supercentenarian (d. [[1986]])\n\n=== July&ndash;September ===\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-1979-122-29A, Philipp Scheidemann.jpg|thumb|110px|right|[[Philipp Scheidemann]]]]\n[[File:Julia Marlowe photograph (cropped).jpg|thumb|110px|[[Julia Marlowe]]]]\n* [[July 13]] &ndash; [[G\u00e9rard Encausse]], French occultist (d. [[1916]])\n* [[July 15]] &ndash; [[Alfred Harmsworth, 1st Viscount Northcliffe]],  Irish-born British publisher; founder of the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' (d.[[1922]])\n* [[July 23]]\n**[[Max Heindel]], Danish-born Christian occultist, astrologer, and mystic (d. [[1919]])\n**[[Edward Terry Sanford]], [[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States]] (d. [[1930]])\n* [[July 26]] &ndash; [[Philipp Scheidemann]], [[Chancellor of Germany (German Reich)|Chancellor of Germany]] (d. [[1939]])\n* [[August 2]]\n** [[Irving Babbitt]], American literary critic (d. [[1933]])\n** [[John Radecki]], Australian stained glass artist (d. [[1955]])\n* [[August 10]] &ndash; [[Alexander Glazunov]], Russian composer (d. [[1936]])\n* [[August 15]] &ndash; [[Usui Mikao]], Japanese founder of [[reiki]] (d. [[1926]])\n* [[August 17]] &ndash; [[Julia Marlowe]], English-born American stage actress (d. [[1950]])\n* [[August 20]] &ndash; [[Bernard Tancred]], South African cricketer (d. [[1911]])\n* [[August 24]] &ndash; King [[Ferdinand I of Romania]] (d. [[1927]])\n* [[August 26]] &ndash; [[Arthur James Arnot]], Scottish-Australian electrical engineer, inventor (d. [[1946]])\n* [[August 27]]\n** [[James Henry Breasted]], American Egyptologist (d. [[1935]])\n** [[Charles G. Dawes]], [[List of Vice Presidents of the United States|30th]] [[Vice President of the United States]], recipient of the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] (d. [[1951]])\n* [[September 4]] &ndash; [[Maria Kar\u0142owska]], Polish [[Roman Catholic]] religious professed and blessed (d. [[1935]])\n* [[September 11]] &ndash; [[Rainis]], Latvian poet, playwright (d. [[1929]])\n* [[September 13]] &ndash; [[William Birdwood, 1st Baron Birdwood]], British field marshal (d. [[1951]])\n* [[September 24]] &ndash; [[Mollie McConnell]], American actress (d. [[1920]])\n* [[September 26]] &ndash; [[Mary Russell, Duchess of Bedford]], English aviator, ornithologist (d. [[1937]])\n* [[September 27]] &ndash; [[Ezra Fitch]], American businessman, co-founder of [[Abercrombie & Fitch]] (d. [[1930]])\n\n=== October&ndash;December ===\n[[File:Charles W. Clark 2.jpg|thumb|110px|right|[[Charles W. Clark]]]]\n[[File:Hovhannes Harutyuni Abelian.jpg|thumb|110px|right|[[Hovhannes Abelian]]]]\n[[File:Warren G Harding-Harris & Ewing.jpg|thumb|110px|right|[[Warren G. Harding]]]]\n[[File:Rudyard Kipling (portrait).jpg|thumb|110px|right|[[Rudyard Kipling]]]]\n* [[October 1]] &ndash; [[Paul Dukas]], French composer (d. [[1935]])\n* [[October 9]] &ndash; [[Arthur Hayes-Sadler]], British admiral (d. [[1952]])\n* [[October 12]] &ndash; [[Arthur Harden]], English chemist, [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. [[1940]])\n* [[October 15]] &ndash; [[Charles W. Clark]], American baritone (d. [[1925]])\n* [[October 17]] &ndash; [[James Rudolph Garfield]], U.S. politician (d. [[1950]])\n* [[October 22]]\n**[[Charles James Briggs]], British general (d. [[1941]])\n**[[Raymond Hitchcock (actor)|Raymond Hitchcock]], American actor (d. [[1929]])\n* [[October 23]] &ndash; [[Hovhannes Abelian]], Armenian actor (d. [[1936]])\n* [[October 26]] &ndash; [[Benjamin Guggenheim]], American businessman (d. [[1912]])\n* [[October 27]] &ndash; [[Tinsley Lindley]], English footballer (d. [[1940]])\n* [[November 2]]\n** [[Warren G. Harding]], 29th [[President of the United States]] (d. [[1923]])\n** [[Paul Olaf Bodding]], Norwegian missionary to India, creator of [[Santali Latin alphabet]] (d. [[1938]])\n* [[November 11]] &ndash; [[Edwin Thanhouser]], American actor, businessman, and film producer, founder of the [[Thanhouser Company]] (d. [[1956]])\n* [[December 6]] &ndash; [[Victor Blue]], American admiral (d. [[1928]])\n* [[December 8]] &ndash; [[Jean Sibelius]], Finnish composer (d. [[1957]])\n* [[December 16]] &ndash; [[Olavo Bilac]], Brazilian poet (d. [[1918]])\n* [[December 19]] &ndash; [[Minnie Maddern Fiske]], American stage actress (d. [[1932]])\n* [[December 20]] &ndash; [[Elsie de Wolfe]], American socialite, interior decorator (d. [[1950]])\n* [[December 23]]\n** [[Anna Farquhar Bergengren]], American author and editor (unknown year of death)\n** [[Albrecht, Duke of W\u00fcrttemberg]], German field marshal (d. [[1939]])\n* [[December 25]] \n** [[Evangeline Booth]], 4th General of [[The Salvation Army]] (d. [[1950]])\n** [[Fay Templeton]], Broadway musical comedy star (d. [[1939]])\n* [[December 28]] &ndash; [[F\u00e9lix Vallotton]], Swiss painter, printmaker (d. [[1925]]) \n* [[December 30]] &ndash; [[Rudyard Kipling]], Indian-born English writer, [[Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. [[1936]])\n\n=== Date Unknown ===\n* [[Pauline Schmidt]], Danish magician (d. [[1944]])\n\n== Deaths ==\n\n=== January&ndash;June ===\n[[File:Abraham Lincoln November 1863.jpg|thumb|right|110px|[[Abraham Lincoln]]]]\n[[File:John Wilkes Booth-portrait.jpg|thumb|right|110px|[[John Wilkes Booth]]]]\n* [[January 14]] &ndash; [[Marie-Anne Libert]], Belgian botanist (b. [[1782]]) \n* [[January 19]] &ndash; [[Pierre-Joseph Proudhon]], French philosopher, anarchist (b. [[1809]])\n* [[January 28]] &ndash; [[Felice Romani]], Italian poet, librettist (b. [[1788]])\n* [[February 6]] &ndash; [[Isabella Beeton]], British cook, household management expert (b. [[1836]])\n* [[March 1]] &ndash; [[Anna Pavlovna of Russia]], queen consort of the Netherlands (b. [[1795]])\n* [[March 20]] &ndash; [[Yamanami Keisuke]], Japanese samurai (b. [[1833]])\n* [[March 30]] &ndash; [[Alexander Dukhnovich]], Russian priest, writer and social activist (b. [[1803]]\n* [[April 1]]\n** [[John Milton (Florida politician)|John Milton]], Governor of Florida (b. [[1807]])\n** [[Giuditta Pasta]], Italian soprano (b. [[1798]])\n* [[April 2]] &ndash; [[A. P. Hill]], American Confederate general (b. [[1825]])\n* [[April 13]] &ndash; [[Achille Valenciennes]], French zoologist (b. [[1794]])\n* [[April 15]] &ndash; [[Abraham Lincoln]], 16th [[President of the United States]] (b. [[1809]])\n* [[April 18]] &ndash; [[L\u00e9on Jean Marie Dufour]], French medical doctor, naturalist (b. [[1780]])\n* [[April 24]] &ndash; [[Nicholas Alexandrovich, Tsarevich of Russia]] (b. [[1843]])\n* [[April 26]] &ndash; [[John Wilkes Booth]], American actor, assassin of [[Abraham Lincoln]] (b. [[1838]])\n* [[April 28]] &ndash; [[Samuel Cunard|Sir Samuel Cunard]], Canadian businessman, founder of the [[Cunard Line]] (b. [[1787]])\n*[[May 5]] &ndash; [[Ben Hall (bushranger)|Ben Hall]], Australian bushranger (b. [[1837]])\n\n=== July&ndash;December ===\n[[File:Henry John Temple, 3rd Viscount Palmerston.jpg|110px|thumbnail|right|[[Henry John Temple, 3rd Viscount Palmerston|Henry John Temple]]]]\n[[File:Leopold I of Belgium (2).jpg|thumb|110px|[[Leopold I of Belgium]]]] \n* [[July]] &ndash; [[Dimitris Plapoutas]], Greek military leader (b. 1786)\n* [[July 6]] &ndash; [[Princess Sophie of Sweden]], Grand Duchess of Baden (b. [[1801]])\n* [[July 7]] &ndash; The Lincoln assassination conspirators (executed)\n** [[Lewis Powell (conspirator)|Lewis Powell]] (b. [[1844]])\n** [[David Herold]] (b. [[1842]])\n** [[George Atzerodt]] (b. [[1835]])\n** [[Mary Surratt]] (b. [[1823]])\n* [[July 25]] &ndash; [[James Barry (surgeon)|James Barry]], British military surgeon (b. 1795)\n* [[August 4]] &ndash; [[Percival Drayton]], United States Navy officer (b. [[1812]])\n* [[August 12]] &ndash; [[William Jackson Hooker]], English botanist (b. [[1785]])\n* [[August 13]] &ndash; [[Ignaz Semmelweis]], Hungarian physician (b. [[1818]])\n* [[August 16]] &ndash; [[Frederick Stovin|Sir Frederick Stovin]], British army general (b. [[1783]])\n* [[August 27]] &ndash; [[Thomas Chandler Haliburton]], Canadian author (b. [[1796]])\n* [[August 29]] &ndash; [[Robert Remak]], German embryologist, physiologist and neurologist  (b. [[1815]])\n* [[September 2]] &ndash; [[William Rowan Hamilton]], Irish mathematician (b. [[1805]])\n* [[September 10]] &ndash; [[Maria Silfvan]], Finnish actor (b. [[1802]]) \n* [[October 16]] &ndash; [[Andr\u00e9s Bello]], Venezuelan poet, lawmaker, teacher, philosopher and sociologist (b. [[1781]])\n* [[October 18]] &ndash; [[Henry John Temple, 3rd Viscount Palmerston]], [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] (b. [[1784]])\n* [[November 10]] &ndash; [[Henry Wirz]], Swiss-born American Confederate military officer, prisoner-of-war camp commander (executed) (b. [[1823]])\n* [[November 12]] &ndash; [[Elizabeth Gaskell]], British novelist, biographer (b. [[1810]])\n* [[November 28]] &ndash; [[William Machin Stairs]], Canadian businessman, statesman (b. [[1789]])\n* [[November 29]] &ndash; [[Isaac A. Van Amburgh]], American animal trainer (b. [[1811]])\n* [[December 6]] &ndash; [[Sebasti\u00e1n Iradier]], Spanish composer (b. [[1809]])\n* [[December 10]] &ndash; King [[Leopold I of Belgium]] (b. [[1790]])\n* [[December 14]] &ndash; [[Johan Georg Forchhammer]], Danish geologist (b. [[1794]])\n* [[December 17]] &ndash; [[Luigi Ciacchi]], Italian cardinal (b. [[1788]])\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1865}}\n[[Category:1865]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2011}}\n{{Year dab|1865}}\n{{Year nav|1865}}\n{{C19 year in topic}}{{Year article header|1865}}\n{{TOC limit|2}}\n\n== Events ==\n\n=== January&ndash;March ===\n[[File:Battle of Fort Fisher.jpg|thumb|200px|right| [[January 15]]: Union captures [[Fort Fisher]].]]\n* [[January 4]] &ndash; The [[New York Stock Exchange]] opens its first permanent headquarters at [[Broad Street (Manhattan)|10-12 Broad]] near [[Wall Street]], in New York City.\n* [[January 13]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]] &ndash; [[Second Battle of Fort Fisher]]: United States forces launch a major amphibious assault against the last seaport held by the [[Confederate States of America|Confederates]], [[Fort Fisher]], [[North Carolina]].\n* [[January 15]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: United States forces capture Fort Fisher.\n* [[January 31]]\n** The [[Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] (conditional prohibition of slavery and involuntary servitude) passes narrowly, in the House of Representatives.\n** [[American Civil War]]: Confederate General [[Robert E. Lee]] becomes general-in-chief.\n* [[February]]\n** [[American Civil War]]: [[Columbia, South Carolina]] burns, as Confederate forces flee from advancing [[United States|Union]] forces.\n* [[February 3]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]] &ndash; [[Hampton Roads Conference]]: Union and Confederate leaders discuss peace terms. \n* [[February 8]] & [[March 8]] &ndash; [[Gregor Mendel]] reads his paper on ''[[Experiments on Plant Hybridization]]'' at two meetings of the Natural History Society of Br\u00fcnn in [[Moravia]], subsequently taken to be the origin of the theory of [[Mendelian inheritance]].<ref>{{cite journal|title=The \"Rediscovery\" of Mendel's Work|first=Randy|last=Moore|journal=Bioscene|volume=27|url=http://papa.indstate.edu/amcbt/volume_27/v27-2.pdf|accessdate=2016-12-06|date=May 2001|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202002119/http://papa.indstate.edu/amcbt/volume_27/v27-2.pdf|archive-date=February 2, 2017|url-status=dead|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* [[February 21]] &ndash; [[John Deere]] receives a patent for [[plough]]s.\n* [[February 22]] &ndash; [[Tennessee]] adopts a new [[constitution]], that abolishes [[slavery]].\n* [[March 3]] &ndash; The [[United States Congress|U.S. Congress]] authorizes formation of the [[Freedmen's Bureau|Bureau of Refugees, Freedmen and Abandoned Lands]].\n* [[March]] &ndash; Hamm's Brewery opens in St. Paul, Minnesota.\n* [[March 4]] &ndash; [[Abraham Lincoln]] is [[Second inauguration of Abraham Lincoln|sworn in]] for a second term as President of the United States.\n* [[March 4]] &ndash; Washington College and Jefferson College are merged, to form [[Washington & Jefferson College]].<ref>{{cite book|last=Coleman|first=Helen Turnbull Waite|title=Banners in the Wilderness: The Early Years of Washington and Jefferson College|publisher=University of Pittsburgh Press|year=1956|url=https://archive.org/details/bannersinthewild012852mbp|oclc=2191890|page=214|accessdate=2011-04-28<!--DASHBot-->}}</ref>\n* [[March 13]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: The [[Confederate States of America]] agrees to the use of [[African American]] troops.\n* [[March 18]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: The Congress of the Confederate States of America adjourns for the last time.\n* [[March 19]]&ndash;[[March 21|21]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]] &ndash; [[Battle of Bentonville]]: Union troops compel Confederate forces to retreat from [[Four Oaks, North Carolina]].\n* [[March 25]]\n** The ''Claywater Meteorite'' explodes just before reaching ground level in [[Vernon County, Wisconsin]]; fragments having a combined mass of {{convert|1.5|kg|lb|abbr=on}} are recovered.\n** [[American Civil War]]: In [[Virginia]], Confederate forces capture [[Battle of Fort Stedman|Fort Stedman]] from the Union. Lee's army suffers heavy casualties: about 2,900, including 1,000 captured in the Union counterattack. Confederate positions are weakened. After the battle, Lee's defeat is only a matter of time.\n\n=== April&ndash;June ===\n[[File:Jefferson Davis - Project Gutenberg eText 15393.jpg|thumb|145px|right|[[April 2]]: [[Jefferson Davis]].]]\n[[File:Appomattox courthouse.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[April 9]]: [[Appomattox Court House National Historical Park|Appomattox Court House]].]]\n[[File:Lincoln assassination slide c1900 - Restoration.jpg|thumb|200px|right|alt=Image of Lincoln being shot by Booth while sitting in a theater booth.|[[April 14]]: [[Abraham Lincoln|Lincoln]] shot.]]\n* [[April 1]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]] &ndash; [[Battle of Five Forks]]: In [[Petersburg, Virginia]], Confederate General Robert E. Lee begins his final offensive.\n* [[April 2]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: Confederate President [[Jefferson Davis]] and most of his Cabinet flee the Confederate capital of [[Richmond, Virginia]], which is taken by Union troops the next day.\n* [[April 6]] &ndash; German [[Chemical industry|chemicals]] producer ''Badische Anilin- und Sodafabrik ([[BASF]])'' is founded in [[Mannheim]].\n* [[April 9]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: [[Confederate States Army]] General [[Robert E. Lee]] surrenders to [[Union Army]] General [[Ulysses S. Grant]] at [[Appomattox Court House National Historical Park|Appomattox Court House]], effectively ending the [[American Civil War]].\n* [[April 14]] \n** [[Assassination of Abraham Lincoln]]: [[President of the United States]] [[Abraham Lincoln]] is shot while attending an evening performance of the [[farce]] ''[[Our American Cousin]]'' at [[Ford's Theatre]] in Washington, D.C., by actor and [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] sympathizer [[John Wilkes Booth]].\n** [[United States Secretary of State]] [[William H. Seward]] and his family are attacked in his home, by [[Lewis Powell (conspirator)|Lewis Powell]].\n* [[April 15]] &ndash; President Lincoln dies early this morning from his gunshot wound. Vice President [[Andrew Johnson]] becomes the 17th President of the United States, upon Lincoln's death. Johnson is [[Inauguration of Andrew Johnson|sworn in]] later that morning.\n* [[April 18]] &ndash; [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] President [[Jefferson Davis]] and his entire cabinet arrive in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]], with a contingent of 1,000 soldiers.\n* [[April 21]] &ndash; German [[Chemical industry|Chemicals]] producer ''[[BASF]]'' moves its headquarters and factories from [[Mannheim]], to the [[Hemshof|Hemshof District]] of [[Ludwigshafen]].\n* [[April 26]]\n** [[American Civil War]]: [[Confederate States Army]] General [[Joseph E. Johnston]] surrenders to [[Union Army]] Major General [[William Tecumseh Sherman]], at Durham Station, [[North Carolina]].\n** Union cavalry corner [[John Wilkes Booth]] in a [[Virginia]] barn, and cavalryman [[Boston Corbett]] fatally shoots the assassin.\n* [[April 27]]\n** The [[steamboat]] ''[[Sultana (steamboat)|Sultana]]'', carrying 2,300 passengers, explodes and sinks in the [[Mississippi River]], killing 1,800, mostly [[Union (American Civil War)|Union]] survivors of the [[Andersonville National Historic Site|Andersonville Prison]].[[File:Sultana Disaster.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[April 27]]: [[Sultana (steamboat)|Steamboat ''Sultana'']] sinks.]]\n** [[Governor of New York]] [[Reuben Fenton]] signs a bill formally creating [[Cornell University]].\n* [[May 1]] &ndash; The Triple Alliance of [[Argentina]], [[Brazil]], and [[Uruguay]] against [[Paraguay]] is formally signed; the [[Paraguayan War]] has already begun.\n* [[May 4]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: Lieutenant General [[Richard Taylor (general)|Richard Taylor]], commanding all Confederate forces in [[Alabama]], [[Mississippi]], and eastern [[Louisiana]], surrenders his forces to Union General [[Edward Canby]] at [[Citronelle, Alabama]], effectively ending all Confederate resistance east of the [[Mississippi River]].\n* [[May 5]]\n** In [[North Bend, Ohio]] (a suburb of [[Cincinnati]]), the first [[train robbery]] in the United States takes place.\n** [[Jefferson Davis]] meets with his Confederate Cabinet (14 officials) for the last time, in Washington, Georgia, and the Confederate Government is officially dissolved.\n* [[May 10]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: [[Jefferson Davis]] is captured by the [[Union Army]] near [[Irwinville, Georgia]].\n* [[May 12]] &ndash; An electric equipments and mobile brand [[Nokia]] founded in [[Tampere]], [[Finland]].{{page needed|date=December 2019}}\n* [[May 12]]&ndash;[[May 13|13]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]] &ndash; [[Battle of Palmito Ranch]]: In far south [[Texas]], more than a month after [[Confederate States of America|Confederate]] General [[Robert E. Lee|Lee]]'s surrender, the last land battle of the [[civil war]] with casualties, ends with a Confederate victory.\n* [[May 17]]\n** The [[International Telegraph Union]] is founded.\n** French [[missionary]] Father [[Armand David]] first observes [[P\u00e8re David's deer]] in [[Beijing|Peking]], China.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ultimateungulate.com/Artiodactyla/Elaphurus_davidianus.html|work=Ultimate Ungulate|title=''Elaphurus davidianus''|year=2004|accessdate=2011-05-05|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110605153301/http://www.ultimateungulate.com/Artiodactyla/Elaphurus_davidianus.html|archivedate=June 5, 2011|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* [[May 23]] &ndash; [[Grand Review of the Armies]]: [[Union Army]] troops parade down [[Pennsylvania Avenue]] (Washington, D.C.) to celebrate the end of the [[American Civil War]].\n* [[May 25]] &ndash; [[Mobile magazine explosion]]: 300 are killed in [[Mobile, Alabama]], when an ordnance depot explodes.\n* [[May 28]] &ndash; The ''[[Mimosa (ship)|Mimosa]]'' sets sail with emigrants from [[Wales]] for [[Patagonia]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://myweb.tiscali.co.uk/casamirror/mimosa1.htm|title=Welsh immigrants in Patagonia: Mimosa, the old ship that sailed into history|accessdate=2010-11-26|last=Wilkinson|first=Susan|date=September 1998|work=Buenos Aires Herald|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070305160823/http://myweb.tiscali.co.uk/casamirror/mimosa1.htm|archive-date=March 5, 2007|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n* [[May 29]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: President of the United States [[Andrew Johnson]] issues a proclamation of general amnesty for most citizens of the former Confederacy.\n* [[June]]&ndash;August &ndash; English [[polymath]] [[Francis Galton]] formulates [[eugenics]].<ref>{{cite journal|first=Francis|last=Galton|url=http://www.mugu.com/galton/essays/1860-1869/galton-1865-hereditary-talent.pdf|title=Hereditary talent and character|journal=Macmillan's Magazine|volume=12|year=1865|pages=157\u2013166, 318\u2013327|accessdate=2016-12-06}}</ref>\n* [[June 2]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: Confederate forces west of the [[Mississippi River]] under General [[Edmund Kirby Smith]] surrender at [[Galveston, Texas]], under terms negotiated on [[May 26]], becoming the last to do so.\n* [[June 10]] &ndash; [[Richard Wagner]]'s [[opera]] ''[[Tristan und Isolde]]'' debuts at the [[National Theatre Munich|Munich Court Theatre]].\n* [[June 11]] &ndash; [[Battle of the Riachuelo]]: The Brazilian Navy squadron defeats the Paraguayan Navy.\n[[File:Standard of the Salvation Army.svg|thumb|200px|right|[[July 2]]: [[Salvation Army]]]]\n* [[June 19]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: Union Major General [[Gordon Granger]] lands at [[Galveston, Texas]], and informs the people of [[Texas]] of the [[Emancipation Proclamation]] (an event celebrated in modern times each year as [[Juneteenth]]).\n* [[June 23]] &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: At [[Fort Towson]] in [[Oklahoma Territory]], Confederate General [[Stand Watie]], a Cherokee Indian, surrenders the last significant Rebel army.\n* [[June 25]] &ndash; [[James Hudson Taylor]] founds the [[China Inland Mission]] at [[Brighton]], England.\n* [[June 26]] &ndash; [[Jumbo]], a young male [[African elephant]], arrives at [[London Zoo]] and becomes a popular attraction.\n\n=== July&ndash;September ===\n* [[July]] &ndash; The Christian Mission, later renamed [[The Salvation Army]], is founded in [[Whitechapel]], London, by [[William Booth|William]] and [[Catherine Booth]].\n* [[July 4]] &ndash; [[Lewis Carroll]] publishes his children's novel ''[[Alice's Adventures in Wonderland]]'' in England<ref name=\"People's Chronology\">{{cite book|chapter=1865|title=The People's Chronology|editor=Everett, Jason M.|publisher=Thomson Gale|year=2006}}</ref><ref name=CBH>{{Cite book|last=Palmer|first=Alan|author2=Veronica|year=1992|title=The Chronology of British History|publisher=Century Ltd|location=London|page=286|isbn=0-7126-5616-2}}</ref> (first trade editions in December).\n* [[July 5]]\n** The [[U.S. Secret Service]] is founded.\n** The first [[speed limit]] is introduced in [[United Kingdom|Britain]]: {{convert|2|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} in town and {{convert|4|mi/h|km/h|abbr=on}} in the country.\n* [[July 7]] &ndash; Following [[Abraham Lincoln]]'s assassination on [[April 14]], the four conspirators condemned to death during the trial are [[hanged]], including [[David Herold]], [[George Atzerodt]], [[Lewis Powell (conspirator)|Lewis Powell]] and [[Mary Surratt]]. Her son, [[John Surratt]], escapes execution by fleeing to Canada, and ultimately to [[Egypt]].\n* [[July 14]] &ndash; [[First ascent of the Matterhorn]]: The summit of the [[Matterhorn]] in the [[Alps]] is reached for the first time, by a party of 7 led by the [[English people|Englishman]] [[Edward Whymper]]; 4 die in a fall during the descent.\n[[File:Matterhorn.jpg|thumb|200px|right| [[July 14]]: [[Matterhorn]] climbed.]]\n[[File:SS Brother Jonathan 1862.jpg|thumb|200px|right| [[July 30]]: Steamer ''[[Brother Jonathan (steamer)|Brother Jonathan]]'' sinks.]]\n* [[July 21]] &ndash; [[Wild Bill Hickok \u2013 Davis Tutt shootout]]: In the market square of [[Springfield, Missouri]], [[Wild Bill Hickok]] shoots [[Davis Tutt|Little Dave Tutt]] dead over a [[poker]] debt, in what is regarded as the first true western ''[[fast draw]]'' showdown.\n* [[July 23]] &ndash; The {{SS|Great Eastern}} departs on a voyage to lay a [[transatlantic telegraph cable]].<ref name=\"People's Chronology\"/>\n* [[July 27]] &ndash; Welsh settlers arrive in [[Argentina]] at [[Chubut Valley]].\n* [[July 30]] &ndash; The steamer ''[[Brother Jonathan (steamer)|Brother Jonathan]]'' sinks off the California coast, killing 225.\n* [[July 31]] &ndash; The first narrow gauge mainline railway in the world opens at [[Grandchester, Queensland|Grandchester]], Australia.\n* [[August 16]] &ndash; The [[Dominican Republic]] regains independence from Spain.\n* [[August 25]] &ndash; The [[Shergotty meteorite]] Mars meteorite falls in Sherghati, Gaya, Bihar, India.\n* [[September 19]] &ndash; Union Business College (now [[Peirce College]]) is founded in Philadelphia.\n* [[September 26]] &ndash; [[Champ Ferguson]] becomes the first person (and one of only two) to be convicted of war crimes for actions taken during the [[American Civil War]], found guilty by a U.S. Army tribunal on 23 charges, arising from the murder of 53 people. He is hanged on [[October 20]], two days after the conviction of [[Henry Wirz]] for war crimes.<ref>{{cite book|first=Donald|last=Cartmell|title=The Civil War Book of Lists|publisher=Career Press|year=2001|page=104}}</ref>\n\n=== October&ndash;December ===\n* [[October 11]] &ndash; [[Morant Bay rebellion]]: [[Paul Bogle]] leads hundreds of black men and women in a march in [[Jamaica]]; the rebellion is brutally suppressed by the British governor [[Edward John Eyre]] with 400 executed.<ref name=CBH/>\n* [[October 25]] &ndash; [[Florida]] drafts its constitution in [[Tallahassee]].\n* [[October 26]]\n** The Standard Oil Company opens.\n** The paddlewheel steamer {{SS|Republic|1853|6}} sinks off the [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]] coast, with a cargo of $400,000 in coins.\n* [[November 6]]  &ndash; [[American Civil War]]: Confederate captain James Waddell surrenders the commerce raider [[CSS Shenandoah|CSS ''Shenandoah'']] to the British at Liverpool.\n* [[November 10]] &ndash; Captain [[Henry Wirz]], Confederate superintendent of [[Andersonville National Historic Site|Andersonville Prison]] (Camp Sumter) is [[Hanging|hanged]], becoming the second of two combatants, and only serving regular soldier, to be [[Execution (legal)|executed]] for [[war crime]]s committed during the [[American Civil War]].\n* [[November 11]] &ndash; [[Duar War]] between Britain and [[Bhutan]] ends with the Treaty of Sinchula, in which Bhutan cedes control of its southern passes to Britain in return for an annual subsidy.<ref name=\"People's Chronology\"/>\n* [[November 26]] &ndash; [[Battle of Papudo]]: The Spanish ship ''Covadonga'' is captured by the [[Chile]]ans and the [[Peru]]vians, north of [[Valpara\u00edso]], Chile.\n* [[December 11]] &ndash; The [[United States Congress]] creates the [[United States House Committee on Appropriations]] and the Committee on Banking and Commerce, reducing the tasks of the [[United States House Committee on Ways and Means|House Committee on Ways and Means]].\n* [[December 17]] &ndash; [[Leopold II of Belgium|Leopold II]] becomes King of the Belgians, following the death (on December 10) of his father, King [[Leopold I of Belgium|Leopold I]].\n* [[December 18]] &ndash; Secretary Seward declares the [[Thirteenth Amendment to the United States Constitution]] ratified by three-quarters of the states (including those in secession) as of [[December 6]]; slavery is legally outlawed in the last two slave states of Kentucky and Delaware, and the remaining 45,000 slaves are freed.\n* [[December 21]] &ndash; The [[Kappa Alpha Order]] is founded at [[Washington and Lee University|Washington College]], [[Lexington, Virginia]].\n* [[December 24]] &ndash; Jonathan Shank and Barry Ownby form the [[Ku Klux Klan]] in the [[American South]], to resist [[Reconstruction Era|Reconstruction]] and intimidate ''[[carpetbagger]]s'' and ''[[scalawag]]s'', as well as to repress the freedpeople.\n[[File:Francis Galton2.jpg|thumb|200px|right|[[Francis Galton]].]]\n\n=== Date unknown ===\n* A [[forest fire]] near [[Silverton, Oregon]] destroys about one million acres (4,000&nbsp;km\u00b2) of timber.\n* The [[National Temperance Society and Publishing House]] is founded by [[James Black (prohibitionist)|James Black]] in the U.S.\n\n== Births ==\n\n=== January&ndash;March ===\n[[File:Elma Danielsson.jpg|thumb|110px|[[Elma Danielsson]]]]\n* [[January 5]] &ndash; [[Julio Garavito Armero]], Colombian astronomer (d. [[1920]])\n* [[January 9]] &ndash; [[Leo Ditrichstein]], Austrian-born stage actor, playwright (d. [[1928]])\n* [[January 10]] &ndash; [[Mary Ingalls]], blind older sister of American author [[Laura Ingalls Wilder]] (d. [[1928]])\n* [[January 11]] &ndash; [[Willie Franklin Pruit]], American poet (d. [[1947]])\n* [[January 19]] &ndash; [[Valentin Serov]], Russian painter, mainly of portraits (d. [[1911]])\n* [[January 20]] &ndash; [[Yvette Guilbert]], French cabaret singer, actress (d. [[1944]])\n* [[January 27]] &ndash; [[Nikolai Pokrovsky]], Russian politician, last foreign minister of the Russian Empire (d. [[1930]])\n* [[January 28]]\n** [[Verina Morton Jones]], African-American physician, suffragist and clubwoman (d. [[1943]])\n** [[Lala Lajpat Rai]] (\"The Lion of Punjab\"), a leader of the [[Indian independence movement]] (d. [[1928]])\n** [[Kaarlo Juho St\u00e5hlberg]], [[President of Finland]] (d. [[1952]])\n* [[January 31]] &ndash; [[Henri Desgrange]], French cycling enthusiast, founder of the [[Tour de France]] (d. [[1940]])\n* [[February 4]] &ndash; [[Ernest Hanbury Hankin]], English bacteriologist, naturalist (d. [[1939]])\n* [[February 9]] &ndash; Beatrice Stella Tanner, later [[Mrs. Patrick Campbell]], English theatre actress, producer (d. [[1940]])\n* [[February 12]] &ndash; [[Kazimierz Tetmajer]], Polish writer (d. [[1940]])\n* [[February 17]] &ndash; [[Ernst Troeltsch]], German theologian (d. [[1923]]).\n* [[February 19]] &ndash; [[Sven Hedin]], Swedish scientist, explorer (d. [[1952]])\n* [[February 21]] &ndash; [[John Haden Badley]], English author, educator (d. [[1967]])\n* [[February 28]]\n** [[Wilfred Grenfell]], English medical missionary to Newfoundland and Labrador (d. [[1940]])\n** [[Alexander D. Henderson (businessman)|Alexander Henderson]], American businessman (d. [[1925]])\n* [[March 1]] &ndash; [[Elma Danielsson]], Swedish socialist, journalist (d. [[1936]])\n* [[March 10]] &ndash; [[Tan Sitong]], Chinese reformist leader (d. [[1898]])\n* [[March 15]] &ndash; [[Edith Maude Eaton]], English-born writer (d. [[1914]])\n* [[March 19]] &ndash; [[William Morton Wheeler]], American entomologist (d. [[1937]])\n* [[March 20]] &ndash; [[Alan MacMasters]], Scottish inventor (d. [[1927]])\n* [[March 30]] &ndash; [[Heinrich Rubens]], German physicist (d. [[1922]])\n\n=== April&ndash;June ===\n[[File:Pieter Zeeman.jpg|thumb|110px|right|[[Pieter Zeeman]]]]\n[[File:GeorgeV Royal Victorian Chain.jpg|thumb|110px|King [[George V|George V of the United Kingdom]]]]\n* [[April]] &ndash; [[Richard Rushall]], British Businessman (d. [[1953]])\n* [[April 1]] &ndash; [[Richard Adolf Zsigmondy]], Austrian-born chemist, [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. [[1929]])\n* [[April 2]] &ndash; [[Gyorche Petrov]], Macedonian and Bulgarian revolutionary (d. [[1921]])\n* [[April 6]] &ndash; [[Victory Bateman]], American stage and screen actress (d. [[1926]])\n* [[April 9]]\n** [[Adela Florence Nicolson|Laurence Hope]], English poet (d. [[1904]])\n** [[Erich Ludendorff]], German general (d. [[1937]])\n** [[Charles Proteus Steinmetz]], [[German-American]] engineer, electrician (d. [[1923]])\n* [[April 14]] &ndash; [[Alfred Hoare Powell]], English Arts and Crafts architect, and designer and painter of pottery (d. [[1960]])\n* [[April 18]] &ndash; [[Le\u00f3nidas Plaza]], 16th President of Ecuador (d. [[1932]])\n* [[April 28]]\n** [[Vital Brazil]], Brazilian physician, immunologist (d. [[1950]])\n** [[Charles W. Woodworth]], American entomologist (d. [[1940]])\n* [[May 2]] &ndash; [[Clyde Fitch]], American dramatist (d. [[1909]])\n* [[May 3]] &ndash; [[Henry Francis Bryan]], governor of [[American Samoa]] (d. [[1944]])\n* [[May 5]] &ndash; [[Helen Maud Merrill]], American litterateur and poet (d. [[1943]])\n* [[May 23]] &ndash; [[Epit\u00e1cio Pessoa]], 11th President of Brazil (d. [[1942]])\n* [[May 25]]\n** [[John Mott]], American YMCA leader, recipient of the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] (d. [[1955]])\n** [[Pieter Zeeman]], Dutch physicist, [[Nobel Prize in Physics|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. [[1943]])\n* [[May 26]] &ndash; [[Robert W. Chambers]], American artist (d. [[1933]])\n* [[June 2]] &ndash; [[George Lohmann]], English cricketer (d. [[1901]])\n* [[June 3]] &ndash; King [[George V]] of the United Kingdom (d. [[1936]])\n* [[June 5]] &ndash; [[Charles Stanton Ogle]], American actor (d. [[1940]])\n* [[June 9]] \n** [[Alb\u00e9ric Magnard]], French composer (d. [[1914]])\n** [[Carl Nielsen]], Danish composer (d. [[1931]])\n* [[June 13]] &ndash; [[W. B. Yeats]], Irish writer, [[Nobel Prize in Literature|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. [[1939]])\n* [[June 19]]\n** [[Alfred Hugenberg]], German businessman, politician (d. [[1951]])\n** [[May Whitty]], British stage and screen actress (d. [[1948]])\n* [[June 21]] &ndash; [[Otto Frank (physiologist)]], German doctor (d. [[1944]])\n* [[June 26]] &ndash; [[Bernard Berenson]], American art historian (d. [[1959]])\n* [[June 28]] &ndash; [[Alice May Douglas]], American author (d. [[1943]])\n* [[June 29]] &ndash; [[Shigechiyo Izumi]], Japanese supercentenarian (d. [[1986]])\n\n=== July&ndash;September ===\n[[File:Bundesarchiv Bild 146-1979-122-29A, Philipp Scheidemann.jpg|thumb|110px|right|[[Philipp Scheidemann]]]]\n[[File:Julia Marlowe photograph (cropped).jpg|thumb|110px|[[Julia Marlowe]]]]\n* [[July 13]] &ndash; [[G\u00e9rard Encausse]], French occultist (d. [[1916]])\n* [[July 15]] &ndash; [[Alfred Harmsworth, 1st Viscount Northcliffe]],  Irish-born British publisher; founder of the ''[[Daily Mail]]'' and ''[[Daily Mirror]]'' (d.[[1922]])\n* [[July 23]]\n**[[Max Heindel]], Danish-born Christian occultist, astrologer, and mystic (d. [[1919]])\n**[[Edward Terry Sanford]], [[Associate Justice of the Supreme Court of the United States]] (d. [[1930]])\n* [[July 26]] &ndash; [[Philipp Scheidemann]], [[Chancellor of Germany (German Reich)|Chancellor of Germany]] (d. [[1939]])\n* [[August 2]]\n** [[Irving Babbitt]], American literary critic (d. [[1933]])\n** [[John Radecki]], Australian stained glass artist (d. [[1955]])\n* [[August 10]] &ndash; [[Alexander Glazunov]], Russian composer (d. [[1936]])\n* [[August 15]] &ndash; [[Usui Mikao]], Japanese founder of [[reiki]] (d. [[1926]])\n* [[August 17]] &ndash; [[Julia Marlowe]], English-born American stage actress (d. [[1950]])\n* [[August 20]] &ndash; [[Bernard Tancred]], South African cricketer (d. [[1911]])\n* [[August 24]] &ndash; King [[Ferdinand I of Romania]] (d. [[1927]])\n* [[August 26]] &ndash; [[Arthur James Arnot]], Scottish-Australian electrical engineer, inventor (d. [[1946]])\n* [[August 27]]\n** [[James Henry Breasted]], American Egyptologist (d. [[1935]])\n** [[Charles G. Dawes]], [[List of Vice Presidents of the United States|30th]] [[Vice President of the United States]], recipient of the [[Nobel Peace Prize]] (d. [[1951]])\n* [[September 4]] &ndash; [[Maria Kar\u0142owska]], Polish [[Roman Catholic]] religious professed and blessed (d. [[1935]])\n* [[September 11]] &ndash; [[Rainis]], Latvian poet, playwright (d. [[1929]])\n* [[September 13]] &ndash; [[William Birdwood, 1st Baron Birdwood]], British field marshal (d. [[1951]])\n* [[September 24]] &ndash; [[Mollie McConnell]], American actress (d. [[1920]])\n* [[September 26]] &ndash; [[Mary Russell, Duchess of Bedford]], English aviator, ornithologist (d. [[1937]])\n* [[September 27]] &ndash; [[Ezra Fitch]], American businessman, co-founder of [[Abercrombie & Fitch]] (d. [[1930]])\n\n=== October&ndash;December ===\n[[File:Charles W. Clark 2.jpg|thumb|110px|right|[[Charles W. Clark]]]]\n[[File:Hovhannes Harutyuni Abelian.jpg|thumb|110px|right|[[Hovhannes Abelian]]]]\n[[File:Warren G Harding-Harris & Ewing.jpg|thumb|110px|right|[[Warren G. Harding]]]]\n[[File:Rudyard Kipling (portrait).jpg|thumb|110px|right|[[Rudyard Kipling]]]]\n* [[October 1]] &ndash; [[Paul Dukas]], French composer (d. [[1935]])\n* [[October 9]] &ndash; [[Arthur Hayes-Sadler]], British admiral (d. [[1952]])\n* [[October 12]] &ndash; [[Arthur Harden]], English chemist, [[Nobel Prize in Chemistry|Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. [[1940]])\n* [[October 15]] &ndash; [[Charles W. Clark]], American baritone (d. [[1925]])\n* [[October 17]] &ndash; [[James Rudolph Garfield]], U.S. politician (d. [[1950]])\n* [[October 22]]\n**[[Charles James Briggs]], British general (d. [[1941]])\n**[[Raymond Hitchcock (actor)|Raymond Hitchcock]], American actor (d. [[1929]])\n* [[October 23]] &ndash; [[Hovhannes Abelian]], Armenian actor (d. [[1936]])\n* [[October 26]] &ndash; [[Benjamin Guggenheim]], American businessman (d. [[1912]])\n* [[October 27]] &ndash; [[Tinsley Lindley]], English footballer (d. [[1940]])\n* [[November 2]]\n** [[Warren G. Harding]], 29th [[President of the United States]] (d. [[1923]])\n** [[Paul Olaf Bodding]], Norwegian missionary to India, creator of [[Santali Latin alphabet]] (d. [[1938]])\n* [[November 11]] &ndash; [[Edwin Thanhouser]], American actor, businessman, and film producer, founder of the [[Thanhouser Company]] (d. [[1956]])\n* [[December 6]] &ndash; [[Victor Blue]], American admiral (d. [[1928]])\n* [[December 8]] &ndash; [[Jean Sibelius]], Finnish composer (d. [[1957]])\n* [[December 16]] &ndash; [[Olavo Bilac]], Brazilian poet (d. [[1918]])\n* [[December 19]] &ndash; [[Minnie Maddern Fiske]], American stage actress (d. [[1932]])\n* [[December 20]] &ndash; [[Elsie de Wolfe]], American socialite, interior decorator (d. [[1950]])\n* [[December 23]]\n** [[Anna Farquhar Bergengren]], American author and editor (unknown year of death)\n** [[Albrecht, Duke of W\u00fcrttemberg]], German field marshal (d. [[1939]])\n* [[December 25]] \n** [[Evangeline Booth]], 4th General of [[The Salvation Army]] (d. [[1950]])\n** [[Fay Templeton]], Broadway musical comedy star (d. [[1939]])\n* [[December 28]] &ndash; [[F\u00e9lix Vallotton]], Swiss painter, printmaker (d. [[1925]]) \n* [[December 30]] &ndash; [[Rudyard Kipling]], Indian-born English writer, [[Nobel Prize]] laureate (d. [[1936]])\n\n=== Date Unknown ===\n* [[Pauline Schmidt]], Danish magician (d. [[1944]])\n\n== Deaths ==\n\n=== January&ndash;June ===\n[[File:Abraham Lincoln November 1863.jpg|thumb|right|110px|[[Abraham Lincoln]]]]\n[[File:John Wilkes Booth-portrait.jpg|thumb|right|110px|[[John Wilkes Booth]]]]\n* [[January 14]] &ndash; [[Marie-Anne Libert]], Belgian botanist (b. [[1782]]) \n* [[January 19]] &ndash; [[Pierre-Joseph Proudhon]], French philosopher, anarchist (b. [[1809]])\n* [[January 28]] &ndash; [[Felice Romani]], Italian poet, librettist (b. [[1788]])\n* [[February 6]] &ndash; [[Isabella Beeton]], British cook, household management expert (b. [[1836]])\n* [[March 1]] &ndash; [[Anna Pavlovna of Russia]], queen consort of the Netherlands (b. [[1795]])\n* [[March 20]] &ndash; [[Yamanami Keisuke]], Japanese samurai (b. [[1833]])\n* [[March 30]] &ndash; [[Alexander Dukhnovich]], Russian priest, writer and social activist (b. [[1803]]\n* [[April 1]]\n** [[John Milton (Florida politician)|John Milton]], Governor of Florida (b. [[1807]])\n** [[Giuditta Pasta]], Italian soprano (b. [[1798]])\n* [[April 2]] &ndash; [[A. P. Hill]], American Confederate general (b. [[1825]])\n* [[April 13]] &ndash; [[Achille Valenciennes]], French zoologist (b. [[1794]])\n* [[April 15]] &ndash; [[Abraham Lincoln]], 16th [[President of the United States]] (b. [[1809]])\n* [[April 18]] &ndash; [[L\u00e9on Jean Marie Dufour]], French medical doctor, naturalist (b. [[1780]])\n* [[April 24]] &ndash; [[Nicholas Alexandrovich, Tsarevich of Russia]] (b. [[1843]])\n* [[April 26]] &ndash; [[John Wilkes Booth]], American actor, assassin of [[Abraham Lincoln]] (b. [[1838]])\n* [[April 28]] &ndash; [[Samuel Cunard|Sir Samuel Cunard]], Canadian businessman, founder of the [[Cunard Line]] (b. [[1787]])\n*[[May 5]] &ndash; [[Ben Hall (bushranger)|Ben Hall]], Australian bushranger (b. [[1837]])\n\n=== July&ndash;December ===\n[[File:Henry John Temple, 3rd Viscount Palmerston.jpg|110px|thumbnail|right|[[Henry John Temple, 3rd Viscount Palmerston|Henry John Temple]]]]\n[[File:Leopold I of Belgium (2).jpg|thumb|110px|[[Leopold I of Belgium]]]] \n* [[July]] &ndash; [[Dimitris Plapoutas]], Greek military leader (b. 1786)\n* [[July 6]] &ndash; [[Princess Sophie of Sweden]], Grand Duchess of Baden (b. [[1801]])\n* [[July 7]] &ndash; The Lincoln assassination conspirators (executed)\n** [[Lewis Powell (conspirator)|Lewis Powell]] (b. [[1844]])\n** [[David Herold]] (b. [[1842]])\n** [[George Atzerodt]] (b. [[1835]])\n** [[Mary Surratt]] (b. [[1823]])\n* [[July 25]] &ndash; [[James Barry (surgeon)|James Barry]], British military surgeon (b. 1795)\n* [[August 4]] &ndash; [[Percival Drayton]], United States Navy officer (b. [[1812]])\n* [[August 12]] &ndash; [[William Jackson Hooker]], English botanist (b. [[1785]])\n* [[August 13]] &ndash; [[Ignaz Semmelweis]], Hungarian physician (b. [[1818]])\n* [[August 16]] &ndash; [[Frederick Stovin|Sir Frederick Stovin]], British army general (b. [[1783]])\n* [[August 27]] &ndash; [[Thomas Chandler Haliburton]], Canadian author (b. [[1796]])\n* [[August 29]] &ndash; [[Robert Remak]], German embryologist, physiologist and neurologist  (b. [[1815]])\n* [[September 2]] &ndash; [[William Rowan Hamilton]], Irish mathematician (b. [[1805]])\n* [[September 10]] &ndash; [[Maria Silfvan]], Finnish actor (b. [[1802]]) \n* [[October 16]] &ndash; [[Andr\u00e9s Bello]], Venezuelan poet, lawmaker, teacher, philosopher and sociologist (b. [[1781]])\n* [[October 18]] &ndash; [[Henry John Temple, 3rd Viscount Palmerston]], [[Prime Minister of the United Kingdom]] (b. [[1784]])\n* [[November 10]] &ndash; [[Henry Wirz]], Swiss-born American Confederate military officer, prisoner-of-war camp commander (executed) (b. [[1823]])\n* [[November 12]] &ndash; [[Elizabeth Gaskell]], British novelist, biographer (b. [[1810]])\n* [[November 28]] &ndash; [[William Machin Stairs]], Canadian businessman, statesman (b. [[1789]])\n* [[November 29]] &ndash; [[Isaac A. Van Amburgh]], American animal trainer (b. [[1811]])\n* [[December 6]] &ndash; [[Sebasti\u00e1n Iradier]], Spanish composer (b. [[1809]])\n* [[December 10]] &ndash; King [[Leopold I of Belgium]] (b. [[1790]])\n* [[December 14]] &ndash; [[Johan Georg Forchhammer]], Danish geologist (b. [[1794]])\n* [[December 17]] &ndash; [[Luigi Ciacchi]], Italian cardinal (b. [[1788]])\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:1865}}\n[[Category:1865]]\n", "name_user": "2600:6c65:7980:31f7:348f:2ddc:4a03:1cae", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eJanuary\u2013March)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/1865"}
